{p. 279}

Again, the same author says:

"Job acted as high-priest in his own family; and, minute as are the
descriptions of the different classes and usages of society in this
book, we have not the slightest allusion to the existence of any priests
or specially appointed ministers of religion, *a fact which shows the
extreme antiquity of the period*, as priests were, in all probability,
first appointed about the time of Abraham, and became general soon
